{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505264","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505264"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:28:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:28:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2424"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2424","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2424"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.09,0.85,0.02,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2424"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86464"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2424","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2424"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2424"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70744"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1096"},{"type":"tags","id":"1240"},{"type":"tags","id":"2451"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1829"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1880"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10014"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39789"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86464","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/86464"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department at 36 weeks gestation with spontaneous rupture of membranes 24 hours ago. She reports increasing lower abdominal pain, nausea, and persistent vaginal loss since this time. This is her second pregnancy, with her first pregnancy ending in emergency caesarean section due to placental abruption. Her current pregnancy has been complicated by diet-controlled gestational diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears distressed. Her pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 38.7\u00b0C. Her abdomen is tender in the lower quadrants with a tense uterus. Speculum examination reveals foul-smelling, blood-tinged amniotic fluid. Bedside ultrasound confirms cephalic presentation with oligohydramnios. Cardiotocography shows foetal tachycardia with baseline heart rate 173/min.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Uterine scar dehiscence","Concealed placental abruption","Chorioamnionitis","Obstructed preterm labour","Placenta praevia"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with maternal fever, tachycardia, uterine tenderness, foul-smelling vaginal discharge, and foetal tachycardia. These findings strongly suggest \u003Cstrong\u003Echorioamnionitis\u003C/strong\u003E, an ascending infection of the amniotic cavity. The prolonged rupture of membranes (\u003E24 hours) is a significant risk factor. Diagnosis requires maternal fever plus two or more of: maternal tachycardia \u003E100/min, foetal tachycardia \u003E160/min, uterine tenderness, offensive amniotic fluid, elevated white cell count, or CRP \u003E40.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUterine scar dehiscence\u003C/strong\u003E is a concerning possibility given her previous caesarean section. However, this typically presents with severe, constant abdominal pain, vaginal bleeding, and maternal shock. While uterine tenderness is present, the infectious signs and foetal tachycardia point more strongly toward chorioamnionitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConcealed placental abruption\u003C/strong\u003E is possible given her history of previous abruption. However, this would typically present with severe constant pain, a board-like rigid uterus, and signs of maternal hypovolaemia or foetal compromise. The presence of fever and foul-smelling discharge makes infection more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObstructed preterm labour\u003C/strong\u003E could explain the pain and tachycardia, but would not account for the fever, foul-smelling discharge, or degree of foetal tachycardia seen here. Additionally, there is no mention of regular contractions or cervical changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlacenta praevia\u003C/strong\u003E can present with vaginal bleeding in late pregnancy, particularly in women with previous caesarean section. However, it would not explain the fever, foul-smelling discharge, or foetal tachycardia. Additionally, ultrasound would have identified this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of chorioamnionitis includes immediate broad-spectrum intravenous antibiotics (typically ampicillin, gentamicin, and metronidazole) and urgent delivery, usually by caesarean section given the previous uterine scar.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Chorioamnionitis should be suspected in the presence of maternal fever, tachycardia, uterine tenderness, foul-smelling vaginal discharge, and foetal tachycardia.","Previous caesarean section increases risk of both uterine rupture and abnormal placentation in subsequent pregnancies.","Prolonged rupture of membranes is a significant risk factor for ascending infection and chorioamnionitis."],"references":["Higgins RD, Saade G, Polin RA, et al. Evaluation and Management of Women and Newborns With a Maternal Diagnosis of Chorioamnionitis: Summary of a Workshop. Obstet Gynecol 2016; 127:426.","Kim CJ, Romero R, Chaemsaithong P, et al. Acute chorioamnionitis and funisitis: definition, pathologic features, and clinical significance. Am J Obstet Gynecol 2015; 213:S29."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70744"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2424"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70744","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/70744"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-21T22:28:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-25T21:28:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2424"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86464"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"t